{"id":1169,"text":"#Overview - Dacryoadenitis - 1D80.Y\nDacryoadenitis is an inflammation of the lacrimal gland. Dacryoadenitis may be acute or chronic. Lacrimal gland is located in the superotemporal part of the orbit. It consists of two parts, palpebral lobe, which is visible on eversion of the eyelid and orbital lobe. Secretions of gland form the aqueous layer of the tear film. Dacryoadenitis may be infectious or has systemic aetiology. Lacrimal gland belongs to the lymphoid tissue system and is called mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT). It contains Immunogobulin A (IgA) plasma cells, T cell lymphocytes and few B cell lymphocytes. Dacryoadenitis often lacks the inflammatory signs and may present with enlargement only, then it has to be distinguished from the neoplasm of the gland.","entities":[{"id":17150,"label":"Complication_E","start_offset":57,"end_offset":91},{"id":17154,"label":"Anatomy_E","start_offset":166,"end_offset":198},{"id":17155,"label":"Anatomy_E","start_offset":226,"end_offset":240},{"id":17156,"label":"Anatomy_E","start_offset":289,"end_offset":301},{"id":17158,"label":"Complication_E","start_offset":386,"end_offset":397},{"id":17161,"label":"Anatomy_E","start_offset":453,"end_offset":476},{"id":17162,"label":"Anatomy_E","start_offset":491,"end_offset":531},{"id":17163,"label":"Disease_E","start_offset":628,"end_offset":643},{"id":17157,"label":"Disease_E","start_offset":364,"end_offset":379},{"id":17159,"label":"Cause_E","start_offset":404,"end_offset":422},{"id":17160,"label":"Anatomy_E","start_offset":424,"end_offset":438},{"id":17165,"label":"Complication_E","start_offset":699,"end_offset":710},{"id":17166,"label":"Complication_E","start_offset":758,"end_offset":779},{"id":17148,"label":"Disease_E","start_offset":11,"end_offset":26},{"id":17149,"label":"Disease_E","start_offset":36,"end_offset":51},{"id":17151,"label":"Disease_E","start_offset":93,"end_offset":108},{"id":17152,"label":"Complication_E","start_offset":115,"end_offset":13